<main id="main">
<p class="lead">Owls belong to two main groups: the true owls (Strigidae) and barn-owls (Tytonidae). They inhabit every continent except Antarctica and occupy habitats ranging from dense forests to deserts. They hold cultural significance in many societies — symbols of wisdom, harbingers of mystery, and players in folktales.</p>
<div class="grid-3" style="margin-top:14px">
<div class="feature card" role="article">
<h3>Night vision</h3>
<p>Large pupils and many rod cells let owls see well in low light. They rely on sight to hunt at dusk and night.</p>
</div>
<div class="feature card" role="article">
<h3>Silent flight</h3>
<p>Special feather edges break up airflow and dampen sound — making their flight whisper-quiet for stealthy hunting.</p>
</div>
<div class="feature card" role="article">
<h3>Acute hearing</h3>
<p>Asymmetrical ear placement and facial discs focus sound, allowing owls to locate prey even in complete darkness.</p>
</div>
</div>
</section>


<section id="adaptations" class="card">
<h2>Unique adaptations — a closer look</h2>
<ol>
<li><strong>Facial discs</strong> — act like satellite dishes, directing sound into the ears.</li>
<li><strong>Asymmetrical ears</strong> — time differences between ears let them pinpoint prey in 3D.</li>
<li><strong>Flexible necks</strong> — up to 270° rotation, thanks to extra vertebrae and specialized blood flow adaptations.</li>
<li><strong>Camouflage</strong> — feather patterns blend with tree bark and foliage, helping them remain unseen.</li>
</ol>
</section>


